ce:section.ce:para:
The CQDs were synthesized using a greener approach with the help of reflux method (Scheme 1
                        ) and characterised using various spectroscopic techniques. The optical properties of CQDs were studied using UV–Vis absorption spectroscopy and fluorescence emission spectroscopy. The UV–Vis absorption spectrum (Fig. 1
                        a, Inset) was recorded by taking 5 μL CQDs in 1 mL of MILLI-Q water, which shows two peaks mainly at 265 nm and 320 nm. The peak at 265 nm might be due to the π→π* transition corresponding to C = C bond whereas, the peak at 316 nm might correspond to the presence of n→π* transition due to the presence of C = O bond in the structure of CQDs. [50,51] The fluorescence emission spectra (Fig. 1a) show excitation dependent emission and a red shift was observed on moving from excitation wavelength of 320 nm to 450 nm with a decrease in fluorescence intensity. This trend in the fluorescence intensity might be due to the surface states which are alike to the molecular states, along with the size of CQDs that falls in the quantum dimension which affects the band gap of CQDs and increases the complexity of excited states of CQDs. [52]
